%N A395784 Brick wall numbers: an integer k > 1, written as k = p_1 * p_2 * ... * p_r where p_1 <= p_2 <= ... <= p_r are primes, is a brick wall number if there exist integers h >= 2 and w >= 2 such that the prime factors p_i of k can be stacked up in h horizontal layers of bricks such that the sum of the p_i's in each layer is equal to w.
%C A395784 One can show that the set of brick wall numbers is of zero density. (More results in an article submitted for publication)
%C A395784 All terms for which h=2 form the subsequence A175592. - _Ivan N. Ianakiev_, Jun 06 2026
%H A395784 Alois P. Heinz, <a href="/A395784/b395784.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A395784 For example, 30 is a brick wall number of width 5 and height 2. Indeed its prime factors 2, 3 and 5 can be stacked up as
%e A395784  --------
%e A395784 |    5   |
%e A395784  --------
%e A395784 | 2 |  3 |
%e A395784  --------
%e A395784 Another example, the number n = 5 * 7 * 11 * 13 * 17 * 19 = 1616615 is a brick wall number with height h = 3 and width w = 24. It can be arranged as follows:
%e A395784  -------------------------
%e A395784 |     11    |      13     |
%e A395784  -------------------------
%e A395784 |   7   |     17          |
%e A395784  -------------------------
%e A395784 |  5  |       19          |
%e A395784  -------------------------
%e A395784 It is clear that squares are brick wall numbers of height 2, cubes are brick wall numbers of height 3, etc.
%Y A395784 A246547 is a subsequence.
%K A395784 nonn,new
